      "type": "edit",
      "id": "914c0d63-c79c-4392-b39e-fd072f5808e9",
      "item": {
        "id": "914c0d63-c79c-4392-b39e-fd072f5808e9",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Some centres such as the renin-angiotensin system, control more than one variable. When the receptor senses a stimulus, it reacts by sending an action potential to a control centre. The control centre sets the maintenance range, the acceptable upper and lower limits, for the particular variable such as temperature. The control center responds to the signal by determining an appropriate response and sending signals to an effector which can be one or more muscles, an organ, or a gland. When the signal is received and acted on, negative feedback is fed back to the receptor that stops the need for further signalling."
      },
      "date": 1517401878578
